{"questionId":"2804057","questionHtml":"<p>The functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> are defined for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℝ</mi></math> by</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the two possible functions <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi></math> such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempts to form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>g</mi><mo>∘</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>equates their corresponding terms to form at least one equation&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>15</mn></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>±</mo><mn>2</mn></math> (seen anywhere)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>attempt to use <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn></math> to pair the correct values (seen anywhere)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></math>), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></math> (accept <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[7 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"2804057","referenceCode":"23M.1.SL.TZ2.6","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"The functions f and g are defined for x∈ℝ by f(x)=ax+b, where a, b∈ℤ g(x)=x2+x+3. Find the two possible functions f such that (g∘f)(x)=4x2-14x+15.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"6","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 7]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.5—Composite functions, identity, finding inverse","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.7—Solutions of quadratic equations and inequalities, discriminant and nature of roots","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.10—Solving equations graphically and analytically"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}